diagnoses.name: Hypertensive heart disease
diagnoses.description: A complication of high blood pressure (hypertension) that affects the heart.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A metabolic disease that causes high blood sugar. It can lead to issues with vision, nerve damage, and contribute to periodontal disease.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition where the kidneys do not function correctly. It could be a complication of hypertension.

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)
diagnoses.description: A digestive disorder where stomach acid irritates the stomach lining and esophagus, potentially leading to dyspepsia.

diagnoses.name: Metabolic Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A cluster of conditions that occur together, increasing your risk of heart disease, stroke, and type 2 diabetes. These conditions include high blood pressure, high blood sugar, excess body fat around the waist, and abnormal cholesterol levels.

diagnoses.name: Glaucoma
diagnoses.description: A group of eye conditions that can cause blindness by damaging the optic nerve, often associated with high eye pressure. Vision problems, including difficulty focusing, can be a symptom.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition that causes pain all over the body, sleep problems, fatigue, and often emotional and mental distress. People with fibromyalgia may be more sensitive to pain than people without fibromyalgia. This is called abnormal pain perception processing.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: A potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). It can cause visual disturbances, including difficulty focusing, and increased physical sensitivity.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which your thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormones. It can lead to symptoms such as fatigue, weight gain, and sensitivity to cold.

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.description: A condition in which you lack enough healthy red blood cells to carry adequate oxygen to your body's tissues. It can make you feel tired and weak and can be associated with various chronic conditions.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: HIV/AIDS can lead to a weakened immune system, making the body more susceptible to infections. Lymphadenopathy (swollen lymph nodes) is a common symptom, and some patients might experience increased appetite or nausea due to either the infection itself or side effects of the treatment.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: Lymphoma, a cancer of the lymphatic system, can cause symptoms such as lymphadenopathy, increased susceptibility to infections due to a compromised immune system, and nonspecific symptoms such as nausea. In some cases, increased appetite could also be observed.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: Sarcoidosis is an inflammatory disease that affects multiple organs in the body, most commonly the lungs and lymph nodes. It can cause lymphadenopathy, an increased appetite in some cases, and may lead to complications that include aneurysms and a slightly increased risk of infection due to granulomas affecting various organs.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.description: Behçet's disease is a chronic condition that causes blood vessel inflammation throughout your body. The disease can lead to aneurysms, an increased susceptibility to infections, and symptoms like nausea. Lymphadenopathy may also be present.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: SLE is a chronic autoimmune disease that can affect any part of the body, including the lymph nodes, leading to lymphadenopathy. Patients may experience nausea and increased susceptibility to infections due to both the disease and its treatment. Increased appetite can sometimes be observed, potentially as a side effect of medications like corticosteroids used in treatment.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.description: Tuberculosis, particularly extrapulmonary tuberculosis, can lead to lymphadenopathy. Patients often experience increased susceptibility to infections, and systemic symptoms can include nausea. An increased appetite might occur as the disease is treated and the patient begins to recover.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Mononucleosis
diagnoses.description: Caused by the Epstein-Barr virus, infectious mononucleosis can cause lymphadenopathy, an increased susceptibility to infections, and symptoms like nausea. While an increased appetite is less common, it could potentially be seen during the recovery phase.

diagnoses.name: Syphilis
diagnoses.description: In its secondary stage, syphilis can cause symptoms including lymphadenopathy and generalized illness, potentially including nausea. While increased susceptibility to infection is not a hallmark of syphilis itself, co-infection with other sexually transmitted infections, including HIV, is possible. Increased appetite is not typically associated but could be an indirect effect of systemic illness.

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.description: Certain types of anemia, particularly hemolytic anemia, can lead to symptoms such as increased susceptibility to infections and lymphadenopathy. Nausea and an increase in appetite can occur as nonspecific symptoms or side effects of treatment.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Lymphoproliferative Syndrome
diagnoses.description: This rare autoimmune disorder is characterized by the abnormal proliferation of lymphocytes, leading to lymphadenopathy. It can cause an increased susceptibility to infection and non-specific symptoms such as nausea. Increased appetite might occur but is not a common symptom.

diagnoses: Thyroid Disorders (such as Hypothyroidism or Hyperthyroidism)
Autoimmune Disorders (e.g., Systemic Lupus Erythematosus, Sjögren's syndrome)

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.description: Anxiety disorders, including Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (OCD), can manifest physically and may contribute to symptoms like weight loss and obsessive-compulsive behavior.

diagnoses.Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes (EDS): A group of disorders affecting connective tissues, known for symptoms such as skin hypermobility, which may indirectly relate to the noted hypermobility.

diagnoses.name: Thyroid Disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions such as hyperthyroidism or Grave's disease can lead to symptoms like weight loss, alopecia (hair loss), and may exacerbate anxiety, potentially contributing to obsessive-compulsive behaviors.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Disorders
diagnoses.description: Certain autoimmune diseases can cause alopecia and weight loss, and may have an association with neuropsychiatric symptoms including obsessive-compulsive behavior.

diagnoses.name: Mast Cell Activation Syndrome (MCAS)
diagnoses.description: Though not directly correlated with all listed symptoms, MCAS can have a wide range of manifestations and could theoretically play a role in a complex symptomatology including features like weight loss and allergy-driven reactions potentially relevant to Kounis syndrome.

diagnoses.name: Nutritional Deficiencies
diagnoses.description: Deficiencies in certain nutrients could lead to hair loss and weight loss, and severe deficiencies may impact neurological function, potentially affecting behavior.

diagnoses.name: Cardiac Conditions
diagnoses.description: Given Kounis syndrome is a cardiac-related allergic reaction, underlying or other cardiac conditions should be considered, though they may not directly account for all the described symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Psychiatric Disorders
diagnoses.description: Psychiatric disorders could explain the obsessive-compulsive behavior; however, the relationship with other symptoms would usually be considered indirect.

diagnoses.name: Endocrine Disorders
diagnoses.description: Several endocrine disorders, aside from thyroid problems, can result in weight changes, hair loss, and various other symptoms listed.

diagnoses.name: Dermatological Conditions
diagnoses.description: Primary skin conditions can account for alopecia and may also indicate systemic disease that could relate to the broader symptom profile.

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.description: A type of blood cancer that causes the bone marrow to make too many red blood cells. This can lead to thickened blood and increased risk of blood clots. It might explain polycythemia but usually doesn't directly cause lymphadenopathy or lymphadenitis.

diagnoses.name: Secondary Polycythemia
diagnoses.description: An increase in red blood cells due to another condition, such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease or heart failure. While it accounts for polycythemia, it's less likely to be associated with the other listed symptoms without an underlying unifying condition.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer of the blood and bone marrow that progresses slowly. It can lead to an increased number of lymphocytes, potentially explaining lymphadenopathy. Does not directly cause dyshidrotic eczema but may cause immune dysregulation.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease affecting multiple organs in the body, commonly the lungs and lymph nodes. It can cause lymphadenopathy and has been associated with skin manifestations, though typically not dyshidrotic eczema specifically.

diagnoses.name: Hodgkin Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer originating from white blood cells called lymphocytes. It often leads to lymphadenopathy and can cause a variety of systemic symptoms, though polycythemia is not a hallmark symptom.

diagnoses.name: Non-Hodgkin Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: A diverse group of blood cancers that include all types of lymphoma except Hodgkin's lymphoma. Symptoms can include lymphadenopathy and systemic issues. Not directly linked to polycythemia but can cause secondary symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Mononucleosis
diagnoses.description: An infection typically caused by the Epstein-Barr virus. It's known for causing lymphadenopathy and could theoretically lead to other inflammatory responses, including skin conditions, though not commonly dyshidrotic eczema.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions such as lupus or Sjogren's syndrome that can affect multiple parts of the body, including the lymphatic system and skin, potentially explaining lymphadenopathy and various skin conditions. Autoimmune processes could indirectly affect blood cell production.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.description: A bacterial infection that primarily affects the lungs but can spread to lymph nodes (leading to lymphadenitis) and other parts of the body. It doesn't typically cause polycythemia or dyshidrotic eczema but can have wide-ranging systemic effects.

diagnoses.name: Lymphadenitis specifically due to bacterial or viral infections
diagnoses.description: Infection of the lymph nodes, which could be secondary to a systemic infection affecting other areas of the body. These conditions wouldn't typically cause polycythemia but may explain lymphadenopathy and general immune dysregulation.

diagnoses.name: Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD)
diagnoses.description: A neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by a pattern of inattention and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity that interferes with functioning or development.

diagnoses.name: Obstructive Sleep Apnea (OSA)
diagnoses.description: A disorder marked by repeated episodes of complete or partial blockage of the upper airway during sleep, leading to reduced or paused breathing.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Rhinitis
diagnoses.description: An allergic response causing itchy, watery eyes, sneezing, and other similar symptoms, potentially contributing to congestion.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Sinusitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the sinuses that persists for 12 weeks or longer, despite medical treatment, often causing congestion.

diagnoses.name: Nasal Polyps
diagnoses.description: Noncancerous growths on the lining of your nasal passages or sinuses that can cause congestion and obstructive symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Hypertension
diagnoses.description: High blood pressure, which can sometimes contribute to episodes of epistaxis (nosebleeds) due to the increased pressure on small blood vessels.

diagnoses.name: Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer of the blood or bone marrow characterized by an abnormal increase of white blood cells, which can occasionally present with leukoplakia due to a weakened immune system.

diagnoses.name: Oral Candidiasis
diagnoses.description: A fungal infection in the mouth, which can present as white lesions similar to leukoplakia.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Hemorrhagic Telangiectasia
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that leads to abnormal blood vessel formation and can cause recurrent nosebleeds.

diagnoses.name: Nasopharyngeal Carcinoma
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that occurs in the nasopharynx, located behind the nose and above the back of the throat, which can present with symptoms like nosebleeds, congestion, and obstructive sleep apnea.

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses: Blepharospasm may indicate a condition impacting neurological control of eyelid movement.
Increased susceptibility to infection could suggest an underlying immunodeficiency disorder or chronic disease compromising the immune system.
Vulvodynia, characterized by vulvar pain without an obvious cause, may be related to nerve injury, hormonal changes, or muscular issues.
Irritated eyes can be associated with allergies, dry eye syndrome, or infections.
Tinnitus, often a symptom of underlying conditions such as hearing loss, ear injury, or a circulatory system disorder.
Sjögren's syndrome, an autoimmune disorder that can present with dry eyes (related to irritated eyes) and increased susceptibility to infection due to decreased moisture in mucous membranes.
Multiple sclerosis (MS), a disease where the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves, could potentially explain blepharospasm and an increased susceptibility to infections.

Fibromyalgia, a long-term condition that causes pain all over the body and could explain vulvodynia and increased susceptibility to infection due to its impact on the body's stress and pain responses.
Lyme disease, which can cause a wide range of symptoms, including issues with the nervous system (potentially explaining blepharospasm and tinnitus) and increased susceptibility to infections.
Chronic Fatigue Syndrome (CFS), which can present with a wide range of symptoms including increased susceptibility to infection, tinnitus, and general pain (potentially relating to vulvodynia).
Vitamin deficiency (e.g., Vitamin C, Vitamin D)

diagnoses.description: An endocrine disorder where the thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormone. Symptoms can include fatigue, weight gain, cold sensitivity, and can go on to affect bone density and cause symptoms like osteopenia.

A condition that occurs when the level of vitamin D in the body is too low. It can lead to bone disorders such as osteopenia due to impaired bone mineralization, and can also be associated with general fatigue and insomnia.
A complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that can't be explained by any underlying medical condition. Symptoms can include insomnia, hypersensitivity reactions, and lymphadenopathy.
An inner ear disorder that can lead to dizzy spells (vertigo) and hearing loss. One of its primary symptoms is tinnitus.

A group of mental disorders characterized by feelings of anxiety and fear. Symptoms can include insomnia, hypersensitivity reactions, and sometimes somatic symptoms like lymphadenopathy due to stress.

A group of disorders where the immune system mistakenly attacks the body. Depending on the specific disease, symptoms can include hypersensitivity reactions, lymphadenopathy, and they can also affect the bones, potentially leading to osteopenia.

An infectious disease caused by the Borrelia bacterium which is spread by ticks. Early symptoms can include fatigue, insomnia, and lymphadenopathy. If untreated, it can lead to more severe complications.
An autoimmune disease that mainly affects the body's moist tissues and glands causing dryness. It can lead to systemic complications like lymphadenopathy and hypersensitivity reactions.
A disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory and mood issues. Symptoms can include insomnia and hypersensitivity reactions.
A chronic inflammatory disorder affecting many joints, including those in the hands and feet. Besides joint problems, it can cause fatigue, insomnia, and lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune disease can manifest with a broad range of symptoms including skin lesions similar to migratory patchy macular erythema, and potentially influence osteoporosis through chronic inflammation and steroid use.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: This condition, characterized by the body's immune system attacking its own moisture-producing glands, can lead to external manifestations such as skin issues and potentially contribute to conditions like osteoporosis.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Caused by Borrelia burgdorferi, Lyme disease can cause migrating rashes, joint issues, and nervous system abnormalities that might present as pseudoseizures.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: This rare disorder causes blood vessel inflammation throughout your body, leading to symptoms such as skin lesions and other symptoms might align due to systemic inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Reactive Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: This condition can lead to skin rashes and joint pain; pseudoseizures might be less directly related but could be secondary to systemic effects or stress.

diagnoses.name: Psoriasis
diagnoses.rationale: Psoriasis, especially when associated with psoriatic arthritis, can produce skin lesions similar to what is described and potentially contribute to systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.rationale: Though primarily known for widespread pain and fatigue, fibromyalgia can be associated with a myriad of symptoms including potential skin changes and susceptibility to conditions like osteoporosis due to lack of mobility or systemic inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.rationale: This disease features symptoms of several connective tissue diseases including lupus and Sjögren's syndrome, which can encapsulate a broad array of symptoms including those provided.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.rationale: An inflammation of the blood vessels, which can cause skin eruptions that mimic migratory patchy macular erythema and other symptoms mentioned due to systemic effects.

diagnoses.name: Osteogenesis Imperfecta
diagnoses.rationale: While primarily known for affecting bone strength, it also has potential systemic manifestations that could hypothetically touch upon some of the symptoms given, though it's a less likely candidate for this specific symptom combination.

diagnoses: Eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis (EGPA, formerly Churg-Strauss syndrome)

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)
diagnoses.description: A chronic digestive disease where stomach acid or bile irritates the food pipe lining.

diagnoses.name: Eosinophilic Esophagitis
diagnoses.description: An allergic inflammatory condition of the esophagus that involves eosinophils, a type of white blood cell.

diagnoses.name: Asthma
diagnoses.description: A condition in which your airways narrow and swell and may produce extra mucus. This can make breathing difficult and trigger coughing, wheezing, and shortness of breath.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Rhinitis
diagnoses.description: An allergic response causing itchy, watery eyes, sneezing, and other similar symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Interstitial Cystitis
diagnoses.description: Also known as painful bladder syndrome, it's a chronic condition causing bladder pressure, bladder pain, and sometimes pelvic pain.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Idiopathic Urticaria
diagnoses.description: A condition where hives occur without a known cause, which can include symptoms like angioedema.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic disorder that results in recurrent attacks of edema, or swelling, in various parts of the body, including the stomach, limbs, face, and airway.

diagnoses.name: Mast Cell Activation Syndrome (MCAS)
diagnoses.description: A condition in which mast cells mistakenly release too many chemical mediators, leading to a range of chronic symptoms, including gastrointestinal complaints, skin rashes, and anaphylaxis-like episodes.

diagnoses.name: Zollinger-Ellison Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition caused by a gastrin-secreting tumor or hyperplasia of the islet cells in the pancreas that results in increased acid production, leading to peptic ulcers.

diagnoses.name: Anaphylaxis
diagnoses.description: A severe, potentially life-threatening allergic reaction that can occur very quickly. Symptoms include a rash, low pulse, and wheezing.

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses: Squamous Cell Carcinoma of the oral cavity

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which your thyroid gland doesn't produce enough of certain crucial hormones.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory, and mood issues.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that can't be explained by any underlying medical condition.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease of the central nervous system that disrupts the flow of information within the brain, and between the brain and body.

diagnoses.name: Lupus
diagnoses.description: A systemic autoimmune disease that occurs when your body's immune system attacks your own tissues and organs.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory disorder affecting many joints, including those in the hands and feet.

diagnoses.name: Depression
diagnoses.description: A mood disorder that causes a persistent feeling of sadness and loss of interest.

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.description: A condition in which you lack enough healthy red blood cells to carry adequate oxygen to your body's tissues.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the body has inadequate amounts of vitamin B12, which is essential for optimal neurological function.

diagnoses.name: Hashimoto's Thyroiditis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder in which your immune system attacks your thyroid. This can initially cause hypothyroidism but mediating factors can trigger varied symptoms.

diagnoses: Gastrointestinal disorders (e.g., Crohn's Disease, Celiac Disease)
Sexually Transmitted Infections (STIs) such as Gonorrhea or Chlamydia

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by the Borrelia bacterium which is spread by ticks. It can lead to a wide range of symptoms including fever, rash, facial paralysis, and arthritis.

diagnoses.name: Syphilis
diagnoses.description: A sexually transmitted infection caused by the bacterium Treponema pallidum. Its signs and symptoms vary depending on the stage of the infection and can include ulcers, skin rash, and lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.description: A contagious infection caused by the bacterium Mycobacterium tuberculosis. It primarily affects the lungs but can spread to other parts of the body, leading to a wide range of symptoms.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) is a virus that attacks the immune system. If not treated, it can lead to the disease AIDS (Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome), which makes the body more vulnerable to infections.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease characterized by the formation of granulomas (small areas of inflammation) in various organs, including the lymph nodes and eyes, leading to a wide range of symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Cat Scratch Disease
diagnoses.description: An infection caused by the bacterium Bartonella henselae. It is usually contracted after a scratch or bite from a cat, leading to symptoms such as swollen lymph nodes and fever.

diagnoses.name: Lymphogranuloma Venereum (LGV)
diagnoses.description: A sexually transmitted infection caused by certain strains of Chlamydia trachomatis. It affects the lymphatic system, causing prolonged lymphadenopathy and genital ulcers.

diagnoses.name: Mononucleosis
diagnoses.description: Also known as 'mono' or the 'kissing disease,' this is an infectious illness often caused by the Epstein-Barr virus (EBV). Symptoms include fatigue, fever, rash, and swollen lymph nodes.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that affects the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system), leading to a wide range of symptoms including vision problems and pain.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can affect many parts of the body, including skin, joints, kidneys, brain, and other organs, leading to a wide range of symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Hypersensitivity reactions
diagnoses.description: An allergy-related reaction that could explain increased immunoglobulins, which are part of the immune response. This condition might also cause symptoms like anxiety, leukocytosis (as a response to allergic reaction), and potentially trigger Kounis syndrome, a type of allergic acute coronary syndrome.

diagnoses.name: Respiratory tract infections
diagnoses.description: Infections can lead to symptoms like cough, increased immunoglobulins (as the body ramps up antibody production to fight the infection), and leukocytosis (increased white blood cells). Anxiety could stem from the discomfort and stress of being ill, and if severe enough, could contribute to the development of Kounis syndrome.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune diseases
diagnoses.description: Diseases where the immune system mistakenly attacks the body can cause increased immunoglobulins, leukocytosis, and potentially contribute to symptoms like cough (due to inflammation in the body) and anxiety from dealing with a chronic condition. Autoimmune reactions can sometimes trigger Kounis syndrome too.

diagnoses.name: Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)
diagnoses.description: While primarily affecting breathing, COPD can cause cough and lead to heightened levels of stress or anxiety, potentially contributing to an imbalance that might trigger Kounis syndrome. Immunological responses in COPD could theoretically lead to increased immunoglobulins.

diagnoses.name: Asthma
diagnoses.description: A condition that could explain cough and might associate with increased immunoglobulins, especially IgE in allergic asthma. Anxiety is a common comorbidity in asthma patients. Severe asthma attacks might be linked with complications leading to conditions like Kounis syndrome.

diagnoses.name: Cardiac conditions
diagnoses.description: Underlying heart diseases can directly correlate with Kounis syndrome, given it's an acute coronary event triggered by allergic reactions. Such conditions could also be associated with systemic symptoms like leukocytosis, possibly due to stress or secondary infections.

diagnoses.name: Psychological conditions
diagnoses.description: Anxiety as a primary symptom can worsen or be intertwined with other physical health issues, potentially complicating pre-existing conditions like asthma or allergies, and indirectly affecting immunoglobulin levels through stress responses.

diagnoses.name: Inflammatory bowel disease
diagnoses.description: Though primarily affecting the gastrointestinal tract, conditions like Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis can have systemic effects, including leukocytosis and increased immunoglobulins. Anxiety is also commonly reported among IBD patients and could, in rare cases, involve lung involvement or complications that contribute to cough.

diagnoses.name: Immunodeficiency disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions characterized by abnormal immune responses can lead to elevated levels of certain types of immunoglobulins, leukocytosis as the body attempts to fight infections, recurrent respiratory symptoms like cough, and stress or anxiety due to chronic illness.

diagnoses.name: Pulmonary embolism
diagnoses.description: A potentially life-threatening condition which can present with cough and trigger significant anxiety due to the acute onset and severity of symptoms. While leukocytosis and increased immunoglobulins aren't hallmark signs, they could be secondary to the body's response to the embolism or related complications.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause inflammation and pain in any part of your body. Symptoms often include fatigue, skin rashes, joint pain, and fever.

diagnoses.name: Behcet's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing inflammation in blood vessels. Symptoms include mouth sores, eye inflammation, skin rashes, and genital sores.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare, genetic disorder characterized by severe swelling, particularly of the face, intestinal tract, and airways.

diagnoses.name: Crohn's Disease
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory bowel disease (IBD), causes inflammation of the digestive tract, which can lead to abdominal pain, severe diarrhea, fatigue, weight loss, and malnutrition.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that affects multiple organs in the body, but mostly the lungs and lymph glands. Symptoms can include fatigue, swollen lymph nodes, weight loss, and pain.

diagnoses.name: Familial Mediterranean Fever
diagnoses.description: A genetic condition that causes recurrent fevers and painful inflammation of the abdomen, lungs, and joints.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that begins in the lymphatic system. Symptoms can include swollen lymph nodes, fever, night sweats, weight loss, and fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, serious disorder of the skin and mucous membranes. It's usually a reaction to a medication or an infection. Symptoms include fever, sore mouth and throat, fatigue, and a painful red or purplish rash that spreads and blisters.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the blood vessels that can affect any organ, leading to symptoms such as fever, fatigue, weight loss, muscle and joint pain, and skin rash.

diagnoses.name: Inflammatory Bowel Disease
diagnoses.description: A term for two conditions (Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis) characterized by chronic inflammation of the gastrointestinal (GI) tract, leading to abdominal pain, severe diarrhea, fatigue, weight loss, and malnutrition.

diagnoses: Inflammatory Bowel Disease (Crohn's disease and Ulcerative Colitis)

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses: Inflammatory Bowel Disease (e.g., Crohn's disease, Ulcerative Colitis)

diagnoses.name: Anaphylaxis
diagnoses.description: A severe, life-threatening allergic reaction that can lead to laryngeal edema, hypoxia, and syncope due to cardiovascular collapse.

diagnoses.name: Angioedema
diagnoses.description: Swelling beneath the skin rather than on the surface, which can affect the larynx and cause difficulty breathing, potentially leading to hypoxia.

diagnoses.name: Toxic ingestion
diagnoses.description: Ingestion of toxic substances can lead to a variety of systemic symptoms including vomiting, syncope, and hypoxia due to respiratory distress.

diagnoses.name: Anaphylactic transfusion reaction
diagnoses.description: A severe allergic reaction to blood transfusions, which can cause laryngeal edema, hypoxia, and anaphylaxis.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare, genetic disorder leading to episodes of severe swelling (angioedema) in various body parts including the larynx, which can cause difficulty breathing and potentially lead to hypoxia.

diagnoses.name: Food allergy reaction
diagnoses.description: An immune system reaction that occurs soon after eating a certain food, leading to anaphylaxis, which could potentially cause vomiting, pruritus, and laryngeal edema.

diagnoses.name: Insect sting allergy
diagnoses.description: An allergic reaction to insect stings which can result in anaphylaxis, causing symptoms like vomiting, pruritus, laryngeal edema, and hypoxia.

diagnoses.name: Drug allergy
diagnoses.description: An immune system reaction to a drug that can cause a variety of symptoms, including anaphylaxis, laryngeal edema, pruritus, and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Latex allergy
diagnoses.description: An allergic reaction to the proteins in natural rubber latex, which can cause symptoms ranging from skin irritation and hives (pruritus) to anaphylaxis, including laryngeal edema and hypoxia.

diagnoses.name: Mast cell disorders
diagnoses.description: Diseases affecting mast cells or their mediators, leading to episodic symptoms similar to allergic reactions, including anaphylaxis, hypoxia, and laryngeal edema.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.details: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms. It's frequently characterized by intense, debilitating headaches.

diagnoses.name: Dehydration
diagnoses.details: A condition that occurs when you use or lose more fluid than you take in, and your body doesn't have enough water and other fluids to carry out its normal functions.

diagnoses.name: Viral Gastroenteritis (Stomach Flu)
diagnoses.details: An intestinal infection marked by watery diarrhea, abdominal cramps, nausea or vomiting, and sometimes fever.

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.details: A condition in which you lack enough healthy red blood cells to carry adequate oxygen to your body's tissues, causing fatigue and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Vertigo (Peripheral Vertigo)
diagnoses.details: Often caused by problems with the inner ear. Peripheral vertigo is characterized by dizziness or a feeling that the world is spinning around you.

diagnoses.name: Tension Headache
diagnoses.details: A common type of headache characterized by pain around the head, scalp, or neck, often associated with muscle tightness in these areas.

diagnoses.name: Hypoglycemia (Low Blood Sugar)
diagnoses.details: A condition that occurs when your blood sugar (glucose) level is lower than normal. It can cause headaches, weakness, shaking, and irritability among other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.details: A complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that can't be explained by any underlying medical condition. The fatigue worsens with physical or mental activity, but doesn't improve with rest.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.details: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. It can be benign (noncancerous) or malignant (cancerous). Symptoms can include headaches, weakness, and imbalance.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.details: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. Symptoms can include fatigue, difficulty walking, numbness or weakness, and more.

diagnoses: Autoimmune Diseases (e.g., Sjogren's syndrome, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus)

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic, typically progressive disease involving damage to the sheaths of nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord, symptoms may include numbness, impairment of speech and of muscular coordination, blurred vision and severe fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of migraine that involves neurological phenomena (aura) like visual disturbances (scintillation) before the actual migraine headache begins.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a transient ischemic attack is a brief, temporary disruption of blood flow to the brain, causing stroke-like symptoms such as weakness and paralysis (typically on one side of the body), speech disturbances, and visual issues.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A medical condition that occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Symptoms may include sudden numbness or weakness, especially on one side of the body, confusion, trouble speaking, and loss of vision in one or both eyes.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma (Vestibular Schwannoma)
diagnoses.description: A benign tumor that develops on the balance (vestibular) and hearing, or auditory (cochlear) nerves leading from your inner ear to your brain. Pressure from the tumor can cause hearing loss and imbalance.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barré Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder in which your body's immune system attacks your nerves, leading to muscle weakness and even paralysis. The syndrome can also result in tingling and weakness at first, usually on both sides of the body.

diagnoses.name: Multiple System Atrophy
diagnoses.description: A rare neurological disorder that impairs your body's involuntary functions, including blood pressure, heart rate, and bladder function. Common symptoms include fainting spells, significant changes in blood pressure, erectile dysfunction, motor impairment, and loss of muscle coordination.

diagnoses.name: Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)
diagnoses.description: Often referred to as Lou Gehrig's Disease, this is a progressive neurodegenerative disease that affects nerve cells in the brain and the spinal cord, leading to loss of muscle control.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear causing severe dizziness (vertigo), ringing in the ears (tinnitus), hearing loss, and a feeling of fullness or congestion in the ear. Meniere's disease usually affects only one ear.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by the Borrelia bacterium which is spread by ticks. Early symptoms may include fever, headache, fatigue, and a characteristic skin rash called erythema migrans. If left untreated, infection can spread to joints, the heart, and the nervous system, causing varied neurological symptoms.

diagnoses: Poisoning (including carbon monoxide and heavy metals)

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by visual disturbances and other aura symptoms followed by a severe headache, often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to sound.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear causing vertigo, hearing loss, and tinnitus, which might lead to headaches and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular Migraine
diagnoses.description: A type of migraine where the predominant symptom is dizziness and balance issues rather than head pain, but can include symptoms like headaches, photophobia, and phonophobia.

diagnoses.name: Benign Paroxysmal Vertigo
diagnoses.description: A benign condition in children causing brief episodes of vertigo, possibly associated with migraines, sometimes accompanied by vomiting, but less commonly associated with headache.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: Abnormal growth of cells within the brain, which can cause headaches, nausea, vomiting, and other neurological deficits, depending on the tumor's location.

diagnoses.name: Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by increased pressure inside the skull without a detectable cause, leading to headaches, vision problems, and occasionally, hearing loss.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma
diagnoses.description: A benign tumor on the cranial nerve that affects balance and hearing, potentially leading to symptoms such as hearing loss, tinnitus, and balance issues, which may be accompanied by headache.

diagnoses.name: Temporal Arteritis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory condition affecting the large blood vessels of the scalp, neck, and arms, leading to severe headaches, vision problems, and sometimes phonophobia due to the associated discomfort.

diagnoses.name: Basilar Migraine
diagnoses.description: A rare form of migraine characterized by disturbances in the brainstem or both sides of the brain, often including visual disturbances, vertigo, and sometimes hearing loss or changes.

diagnoses.name: Subarachnoid Hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: A severe and sudden onset headache resulting from bleeding into the space surrounding the brain, possibly accompanied by nausea, vomiting, seizure, or loss of consciousness.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. Symptoms can include sudden weakness, facial drooping, difficulty speaking, and loss of coordination.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: Migraines with aura (complex migraines) include visual disturbances and other neurological symptoms that appear about 10 to 60 minutes before the actual headache begins. Symptoms can include vision loss, tingling in a part of the body, difficulty speaking, and hearing noises or music.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often referred to as a 'mini-stroke,' a TIA has symptoms very similar to those of a stroke but lasts only minutes and causes no permanent damage. Commonly includes speech disturbances, weakness on one side of the body, and numbness.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. It can result in speech disturbances, numbness or weakness in one or more limbs, and partial or complete loss of vision in one eye at a time, typically with pain during eye movement.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Symptoms depend on the size, type, and location of the tumor but often include headaches, speech problems, numbness or tingling in limbs, and vision problems like scotomas.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the brain, often caused by a viral infection. Symptoms can include headache, fever, confusion, a stiff neck, and weakness in the body.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the membranes (meninges) surrounding your brain and spinal cord. Symptoms include a severe headache, fever, confusion, vomiting, and sometimes symptoms like numbness or weakness.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A central nervous system (neurological) disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, and sometimes loss of awareness. Specific types can include symptoms like sudden episodes of sensory disturbance, including visual disturbances and numbness.

diagnoses.name: Lupus
diagnoses.description: A systemic autoimmune disease that occurs when your body's immune system attacks your own tissues and organs. Symptoms include fatigue, headache, confusion, and in severe cases, can also cause seizures and strokes.

diagnoses.name: Cerebral Venous Sinus Thrombosis
diagnoses.description: A blood clot in the brain's venous sinuses which prevents blood from draining out of the brain. Symptoms may include headache, blurred vision, fainting or loss of consciousness, weakness, and difficulty speaking.
